document.title: Ohio’s Learning Standards – Extended with Learning Progressions Science

EA374129A0C74F259949A05EFA52CE4D.description:
Engage with visual representations of the male and female
bodies.

CC41B35C36054D8A8CA9D1AF7B1E7FD2.description: Recognize that you are biologically male or female.

C126D6C20D5B438492E9FDD9C89246D8.description:
Identify what about your body makes you biologically male
or female.

FCAA084ED7C84CD0B1761F9D32B85367.description: Identify the parts of your body that relate to reproduction.

2026BEEB86944C70B5AAFA721214BEFE.description: Sort reproductive organs as male or female.

0800C20E778945D4B2AC9D58BED8EE5C.description:
Identify functions of reproductive body parts as they relate
to being male or female.

55E8F2A78FAA4785BBA58BD291B76800.description:
Identify
structures of the
reproductive system
in a model or visual
representation.

8A620832149140DD8DBB5D88CBCAC2B1.description:
Describe
the function of
the reproductive
system (e.g.,
producing
offspring).

7FFF026C62514A6EA0C019732C7FAD7E.description:
Actively participate in a discussion about what happens
when you drink a lot of liquids.

CBEA3493EDFC46AE841BED78DD939D6A.description: Use pictures to identify the kidneys.

3BA0A3E9136243298DE9030ECD82EEE3.description: Identify what organs are involved when urination occurs.

E5D4B3A0F6EC43F59E87A9F8752ACBC2.description: Identify what lets you know you have to urinate.

7D0891DCAB7B46EDBAC6C8898440DFE8.description: Trace the path of urine through the body given a diagram.

3162ADDF34F14BB78DBB1B3E9BB5BA37.description:
Identify
the kidneys in a
model or diagram
of the body.

C6D9DC5C3CB44978A37561E53EDAF05C.description:
Identify
structures of the
urinary system
(kidneys, bladder, and
urethra).

BBF7F8A065404171BB2F4F9FF77DDAF1.description:
Describe
the main function
of the urinary
system (e.g., to
excrete liquid
waste).

3B848283289F423DB051A02EFF715822.description:
Engage in breathing exercises while using your hand to
feel the movement of air from the body.

62FA79B760E340AD91415589BF2EACBE.description: Identify the lungs in a model or diagram of the body.

D541E8DB2F1042739BDBCDE8C3FB5603.description:
Recognize that your lungs help you to breathe. (e.g.,
breath in and out of a paper bag to watch it expand and
contract).

93D02017217D4589916DB218C8A33CF1.description:
Identify the gases involved in respiration (e.g., take in
oxygen, expel carbon dioxide).

5F7B888D4457479D979AA386600A3A78.description:
Recognize oxygen as the gas required for performing life
functions.

E041DBC823E14EC093EA5511F6FAE764.description:
Recognize carbon dioxide as a waste product expelled by
breathing.

8C0DB962B34F4FAFAB71BDCE985952E9.description:
Observe how breathing changes when exposed to
different conditions. (e.g. breathing on a winter day v.s. a
hot summer day, breathing after you spray body spray or
hair spray).

C539097AD4B04865AB3360311C1D3B81.description:
Recognize that damage to your lungs can make it hard to
breathe.

ECFA9D321A094D829F683894041C00BF.description: Identify things that can cause lung damage.

32508F156FB349BA841DDDC33D1AD233.description:
Describe how disease and damage affect the respiratory
system.

5B1BA2476EE24572B14676B9D4A980BA.description:
Identify
the lungs in a
model or diagram
of the body.

DB15C4522A3944BF874DACD065E5890F.description:
Identify that
breathing is the act
of taking in oxygen
and expelling carbon
dioxide.

605B444BE4AF4E0BB344A463738FD0C6.description:
Describe how the
respiratory system
can be damaged
by disease or
pollutants.

3A7C63A7D4774676886201446C3B0A74.description:
Actively participate in discussion about the path your food
takes as you eat.

AB591B2E2C064A81B972B7402F65B4D6.description:
Recognize that specific organs are responsible for
digesting food.

ED520C18F17A40879ECD1FE11BBD45BF.description:
Identify a digestive organ in a model or diagram in the
body. (e.g., mouth, teeth, tongue, esophagus, stomach,
small intestine, large intestine, and rectum).

F9FF63244EA947F78EE6AC922F4DAABA.description:
Identify the body parts in the mouth (e.g., tongue, teeth,
salivary glands).

E5A4646AAC794853A661BC7F41C04F5F.description:
Consume a cracker and document what the mouth does
(e.g., teeth chew, saliva increases, tongue pushes food
around and back into the esophagus).

C36CDA72996B4328A247150D80029BF1.description:
Using a visual, trace what happens to food after it is
consumed (e.g., from the esophagus it travels to the
stomach, small and large intestine and out the rectum).

9E4CA7FBFEB74DA6833C404EE699B00F.description:
Recognize that the stomach breaks food down for
digestion.

94112D333B6846FEBE0630407DF2B76A.description:
Recognize that as food travels, nutrients and minerals are
absorbed in through the intestines back into the body.

A85189944CAE4AE6997F5B5638CD8278.description:
Identify
a digestive organ
in a model or
diagram of the
body.

2B76C471099545F8A8698841232A07A1.description:
Identify
structures used
in digestion (e.g.,
mouth, teeth, tongue,
esophagus, stomach,
small intestine, large
intestine, and rectum).

58EA935E94644388AFF9FFF8FDD5DB7C.description:
Explain
how the digestive
system functions
to allow humans to
receive nutrients
needed to survive.

5C6F5DF5B86348F6B9BF0E584C371871.description:
Actively participate ein discussion on how the bodyyou
fights illness.

5D1986DE1B8C40C59BCDEF04752FFAB1.description:
Recognize that your body uses certain internal structures
to fight off diseases when you get sick.

A4517FA4C67F44E88E7D0A9BE7A06E07.description:
Recognize that white blood cells are part of the immune
system.

49F75115117A452F92FF838C0D0F9AAE.description:
Describe the role of the immune system in fighting
disease. Relate the immune system to a security system
of a house. It constantly monitors the body looking for
intruders. Once an intruder is detected, it remembers the
intruder and launches a defense each and every time it is
encountered.

DF9A2E7281A64FC3A0E7ABFF9D4FF017.description:
Identify white
blood cells as part of
the immune system.

0E7121E218F442FEABE66C3E50B91E80.description:
Describe
the role of the
immune system in
fighting disease.

DB7A56D15F894D52B58E72B9420364D7.description:
Engage by placing your hand on your heart to feel your
heartbeat.

2A2CF9BCE67240C6B695157BAD819D75.description:
Identify the heart when presented with a diagram or
picture.

611A84D9A0EC46999EC8B96397FCF531.description:
Recognize the heart is a muscle that pumps blood
throughout the body.

8DAD126C57E64855A291695BFAE32297.description:
Use an ECG/EKG printout to provide a visual
representation of a heartbeat.

12887A64A1254292B82363BCAD11A6C5.description: Trace the flow of blood through the heart.

588AB3829318424281679D626FAA5A55.description:
Relate the cardiovascular system to a delivery system,
Blood picks up products and wastes and delivers it to
other systems in the body.

F3A25E5B909F4DDAA50862F8427F0527.description:
Label a representation of the heart including the
chambers.

9449D0307D244068A3A9D2BC65F77107.description:
Locate
the heart on a
diagram/picture.

ACF55B1331B14F82BADC0D1C96EC5ECF.description:
Identify the
heart as a muscle
that pumps blood
throughout the body.

5ECD0290434F4C3B84B710AA7745F9CA.description:
Describe
the structure and
function of the
heart.

CB9F157FEA0E495A96C25FCD49655A2F.description:
Engage in representations of the various components of
blood (e.g., red and white blood cells, platelets, plasma,
etc.).

B73FA38CEA384E60AE658BE554489592.description:
Recognize that there are three different types of blood
cells (e.g., red and white, platelets).

5CA9F9A912E445C0B3E40DAB831ED3D0.description:
Observe pictures of red and white blood cells, describe
differences in their shapes.

9F0FF6F4C1CF4A1E92F78F2F74E4458B.description:
List or select functions of blood (e.g., carry food,
oxygen and wastes, fight infection, maintain balance
(homeostasis)).

E9882EF1D35B43DDA496630E9BC0D4D6.description:
Identify that red blood cells carry oxygen to the entire body
and picks up carbon dioxide to transport back to the lungs.

E74FB9366005403A9B976488BAB7F182.description: Identify that white blood cells fight infection.

4D0262459371413BA0EEF608A6F0D631.description:
Identify the
two types of blood
cells (e.g., red and
white blood cells).

0A3BB0588A394408B32B651D64007316.description:
Describe
the function of blood
in the human body
(e.g., transportation,
protection, and
regulation).

9D60B2F9A6DC4645B8D6A5E1DD8326FA.description:
Describe
the specific
functions of red
blood cells and
white blood cells.

FD6E2FFF99334A718310B2F7DDFA6243.description:
Actively participate in a discussion on growing and
developing.

E2D1DAE0E6704A67A1EF9BB78971D209.description:
Identify hormones as substances that affect growth,
development, and maintenance.

09462992B0134975A019CFE9A4D7EB36.description:
Recognize that hormones regulate body functions from
birth to death.

A12C3E0BD2264957AA516E7C867133A8.description:
Recognize that hormones (chemicals) help to promote
growth in the body and regulate numerous body functions.

13C908BE90984F7F92E62DA34A5C39F0.description:
Recognize that imbalances in the body can lead to
diseases (e.g., uUse diabetes as an example for a disease
that occurs when hormones are imbalanced).

6890242071534B24AC4FA8E6C119D023.description:
Identify that the
body produces
substances to help
bodies grow and
develop.

4A24608A34904008B3E9CF40BF7586E5.description:
Identify
functions of hormones
(maintains blood
glucose levels, stable
blood pressure,
body temperature,
reproduction).

43427D591C7147D7911A1DD46B621AD5.description:
Recognize that
imbalances in
the body can
lead to diseases
(e.g., high
blood pressure,
diabetes).

4836519969464DAF9D09B4906D3A8CEC.description: Smell, touch, listen to, look at, taste various items.

C7CE9892433A4420B9D38119BFEC3E11.description: Match each sense with a body part. (e.g., sight = eyes).

7CF4BCCF0E7244D5A0224071332EF29D.description:
Smell, touch, listen to, look at, taste various items and
compare similarities and differences for each.

1F7F94760B6048B8B7FA6D9703D34113.description:
Describe how you feel or react to items when you smell,
touch, listen to, look at, taste them.

0A4DCCE4099143A08D5175B43C44B316.description:
Match the body organs that are responsible for what you
smelled, touched, heard or saw.

6089CAC280E245FBAEC4898DE1D9CCF1.description:
Recognize that some actions and/or events can cause
involuntary reactions. (e.g., cutting onions makes your
eyes water).

F1BED299B7B7479AA40BEECDE0114E29.description:
Identify
each of the 5
senses using
diagrams or
pictures (e.g., sight
= eyes).

AAF61F5AA9F546D28113620DE059FF2D.description:
Match each
of the five senses
to descriptions or
images of activities
that involve the
senses.

F8E869E118DA476CA30E7A9F0163A1D2.description:
Explain
the connection
between the
senses and
involuntary
reactions.

B4BEDF4768AE4AA0B9FA47AE7E1E6F34.description:
Special Senses
(Sense of Sight, Senses of
Hearing and Balance, Senses
of Taste and Smell)

4E094C2698F54BD09597132C5F2A8793.description:
Engage with a model of a brain or pictures of the brain,
spinal cord, and nerves.

172BA7837FDB49BAAE27630BE21E2B27.description: Recognize a picture of the brain.

9D78C8EC7AB5495AAB9DE1D3179213A4.description: Identify where in the body your brain is located.

6F762E33C78A423F96D552DFA5F8EF38.description:
Identify the skull as what protects your brain and describe
injuries that could affect your skull/brain (e.g., concussion
from sports, car accident, riding bike without a helmet,
diving into shallow water).

738BC4157287478CB2488EBAB070BA85.description:
Recognize that the brain coordinates all the parts and
functions of the body.

BD9D84C9FD5A43B1A2804168668DA9B2.description:
Sort actions into things your body does automatically
(e.g., breathe, digest) and things you have to think about
(e.g.,roll over, throw a ball).

C55BB1CE01754914B4DC5A13A5CAF9FA.description:
Communicate about something that happened to you in
the past, explain that your brain stored that memory.

8764CD6EFE3646A195A14584A9527FD0.description:
Identify
that the nervous
system consists of
the brain, spinal
cord, and nerves.

737F4D5ACC7F4362A6AFAD0210F19723.description:
Identify
a function of the
nervous system
(e.g., muscle control,
memory, sensory
perception, emotions,
speech, balance, and
basic life functions
like breathing).

009A4756CB6F47229E1C6D8E3D5818F6.description:
Explain
how the nervous
system controls all
of the functions of
the body and that
it is made up of the
brain, spinal cord,
and nerves of the
body.

14DF311333AE4B28BA2D32138F9A969B.description:
Engage in moving parts of the body and feeling muscular
structures underneath skin.

75EF81CEC6A844A9AA8CCD5DC9BFE82C.description:
Engage with pictures of the muscular system (e.g., look
at pictures of different muscle types (cardiac, smooth,
skeletal)).

CF23FA7B67474C95ADBD2CCAC7BCE928.description:
Recognize the substance underneath the skin is muscle
and t. That muscles areis attached to the bones of the
skeletal system.

217FC077AB3B4C4BBE2D1D2415E2C1B8.description:
Recognize that different muscles types provide different
functions (e.g., smooth muscles for digestion, striated
muscles for walking, cardiac muscle for heartbeat).

D00760A95CAC443993EE73F7AF7E83F4.description:
Recognize that some muscles move on their own (e.g.,
involuntary).

922B8B2F6F954150918995D3739AD01E.description:
Identify the location of muscles that work involuntarily
(e.g., heart, blood vessels, digestive system).

75964C1D4D4548DD81F02E4F19A99E33.description:
Sort muscles as voluntary or involuntary based on
function.

1D5F54090A924971B22C54505437B771.description:
Bend your arm and leg in and out, notice that voluntary
muscles often work in pairs. One muscle relaxes and the
other contracts.

35CE5BA346A14E5EB1DB9D41F07829C3.description:
Recognize
that some muscle
movements are
voluntary (e.g.,
walking) and some
are involuntary (e.g.,
beating heart).

0E3B11E8FBF34D56BAE2431AB63872C3.description:
Describe how
muscles are
needed for
movement.

E7C2B319BFAB446CB165C7374267567A.description: Engage with a visual model of the skeletal system.

9A5E5655777A4E9892955ABBB17B2B16.description:
Recognize that bones in different parts of the body look
different to provide different functions (primarily support).

7DBD802EA3654AFC934C751965267613.description:
Match body parts with the bones that are associated with
them (head/skull, long bone/extremities, rib cage/chest,
tiny bones/fingers and toes)

244D740D81F94AB4A29CD077EF5C1321.description:
Create a model of a skeleton using the major bones of the
body.

3949FE96B1DC46DDA187C34723CACCAC.description:
List or select the functions of the skeleton (helps you
move, supports the body, protects organs).

B46B536B84A946F4AFAEFF27C85D1AFF.description:
Match
major bones with a
diagram of a body
(e.g., skull=head).

F056A35704B84C71A8CFEBC2319AA266.description:
Complete
a model of a skeleton
using the major bones
of the body.

7A5E2D9EB2184D38B9E2EA166FEAB334.description:
Describe the
functions of
the skeletal
system (support,
protection,
movement).

7467CC45F4D646EBAAFA99CC6F9DF236.description:
Actively participate in discussion of characteristics of own
skin.

381CEF7920B24040AFDA7AD00A3A6ED4.description: Recognize that your skin is a barrier which is protection.

2344189E87C34B07BF7E267A80EE1D46.description:
List or select ways your skin protects you (e.g., keeps
germs out, shields the body from radiation, sweats to
maintain temperature, eliminates waste products).

99B7BABF6E014FDCA3037BE18662F765.description:
View enlarged images of the skin, see that it has layers
and parts which aid in protection.

A651CD64E3284C9F8BAD045D6F426881.description:
Match labels to parts of the skin (e.g., hair follicles, sweat
glands, nerves, blood vessels)

01560613AA7F42888A6C3F122A2D25CF.description: Recognize that skin aids in homeostasis.

23A5A09295254159A8196B88A51D316E.description:
Identify
skin as a form of
protection.

92B21C517D5A463C977DA1442BBD9449.description:
Identify
the functions of skin
(e.g., protection,
temperature
regulation).

7293AFD9A4BE4014AA8183EDF4B833A9.description:
Identify
the accessories
of the skin system
(e.g., nails, hair
follicles, sweat
glands).

4CDAED872CAA4D269C2B42D6D0ECB5AA.description:
Engage with a model of the human body (torso, internal
organs).

800412B51DB64B4CAA10B458EDBB9BBD.description:
Recognize that the human body has universal terminology
for orientation.

9D44D73E8129498485CB393BC15A72A9.description:
Observe a labeled representation of a body and its
organs.

A7908971AFE74E54986FB9EC32536CCF.description: Identify body parts and connect to anatomical terminology.

514D8CC13C354F7FAA081615D433A8DA.description:
Locate
a body part on a
model or image of
a body.

007F9D192F584CB5885EE64AE738C5C5.description:
Match
organ names to a
model or image.

7A8D02FE71574F40A9F91ED303400BA3.description:
Label
organs on a model
or image of a body.

9671BCFC4F0448FF99F1644C19E64D7F.description:
Actively participate in discussion of body functions
including purpose of sweating, shivering, and why heart
rate may increase.

75C9456872904A408C5755950AE756C1.description:
Describe a time when you had a fever, use this to
understand that the body needs to stay at a certain
temperature range.

946551F7E6A44A72BD655A0B708D290F.description:
Describe why you start to sweat or to shake, recognize
these are your body trying return to its proper balance.

B808C9A4F5F948D09320AB0AA24C94FB.description:
Compare heart rate and breathing when sitting versus
running. Discuss why there is a difference.

B78110311B6F4F5698249B6D72149956.description:
Identify why you drink more water when consuming salty
foods..

76D3C3FEDB154F47B7172D3ABE5E2183.description:
Recognize that if more water is consumed, urination
increases.

6D22EC95C861486C81A77A7208FD797A.description:
Recognize that if sweating increases, water will need to be
replaced.

631F29D0E5654B78A55A6C69BD8A1230.description:
Recognize that different parts of the body work together
to maintain homeostasis (e.g., circulatory system works to
support many systems, . Iincreased heart rate increases
blood circulation which imports and exports materials as
needed to maintain a healthy range).

C8DE73399560487BA137A8B6B9A08398.description:
Identify
that the body has
many systems that
work together.

60F9ED55D3B248CDA293153D2719DEEF.description:
Recognize
that the body’s
systems interact to
maintain balance.

3038060A204B4CF5810D99FC28187FC7.description:
Describe
how the body
works to maintain
homeostasis (e.g.,
sweating when the
body is hot).

69470C413AAC4926A30B8B0D786277F6.description:
Engage with visuals showing the composition of various
types of tissues (e.g., many skin cells make up skin
tissue).

0721FC881C0C4E729A5CB08D048F055E.description: Identify that tissues are made of cells.

DC5059A27AED45C0BE0FA3D0233179C1.description: Match pictures of cell types to their related tissue.

C27653D93D434C0FB8F3CF84EFF9D8A1.description: Match types of tissues to their function.

17A34E5A6A2B4393ACEB2147C6991C87.description:
Look at images of various types of tissues and match
them to organs where possible (e.g., cardiac and smooth
tissue).

B582800F89654BB2949368ACBDAF3057.description:
Name either cells or organs that are a part of the various
systems of the body (e.g., cardiac cells make up the heart
which are part of the circulatory system).

E392F21D429F45EB9BC5D27FB534B86A.description:
Identify
that tissues are
made of cells.

2D70A01522FC45D88C622185DF10266F.description:
Recognize
that there are different
types of tissues with
different functions.

859563F587134E34B63FB6332F173B84.description:
Describe
the function of
a particular type
of tissue (e.g.,
muscle tissue).

DDEE09F92EF841D9B0CF1E3C21E50CAE.description:
Engage with pictures or visual models of cells, organs,
and organ systems.

81852E7B6B7544DDA5559CC49272C020.description: Identify that cells make up the human body.

8BAFC9037B474DE684941DD45886F6E8.description: From a group of photos, select the ones that show cells.

8C77AAE829C541F69F68AD78C756FB1D.description: Recognize that cells can work together.

A4201E6925464C93AE6DD463BBCC0E1B.description:
Sequence cards showing cell, tissue, organ and system
into order from simplest to most complex.

73739B25B1C2411FA59565160E2062A0.description:
Identify the functions of the body and the organs/organ
systems that are responsible for that function.

E51C1FC8BC524B0BB3C211D5FFFC0487.description:
Name either cells or organs that are a part of the various
systems of the body (e.g., cardiac cells make up the heart
which are part of the circulatory system).

63487A90A18A4B3F92DBC171AEC1A5DD.description:
Recognize
the hierarchy of
cellular organization
(i.e., cells make
tissues, tissues make
organs, etc.).

A42B0B1BDDD64FF59460AEA832684599.description:
Describe the
function of organ
systems (e.g.,
muscular, skeletal,
digestive, nervous,
respiratory,
reproductive,
digestive).
